and it'll update that data every day or every month or whatever have you.

00:33:08.020 --> 00:33:13.480
Due to some reason, you've got to go back in time and refresh data that AWS updated due to some discrepancy.

00:33:15.060 --> 00:33:16.360
Backfill is sort of how you do that.

00:33:17.220 --> 00:33:19.760
And it works hand in hand with this idea of a partition.

00:33:21.080 --> 00:33:24.180
A partition is sort of how your data is naturally organized,

00:33:24.480 --> 00:33:27.160
and it's like a nice way to represent that natural organization.

00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:31.800
It has nothing to do with the fundamental way how often you want to run it.

00:33:31.880 --> 00:33:36.500
It's more around like I've got a data set that comes in once a month.

00:33:36.600 --> 00:33:37.460
It's represented monthly.

00:33:38.200 --> 00:33:41.240
It might be updated daily, but it's the representation of the data is monthly.

00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:42.700
So I will partition it by month.

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:44.600
It doesn't have to be dates.

00:33:45.020 --> 00:33:45.820
It could be strings.

00:33:46.040 --> 00:33:47.100
It could be a list.

00:33:47.680 --> 00:33:55.580
You could have a partition for every company or every client or every domain you have.

00:33:55.880 --> 00:34:00.160
Whatever you sort of think is a natural way to think about breaking apart that pipeline.

00:34:01.660 --> 00:34:16.919
And once you do that partition, you can do these nice things called backfills, which says, instead of running this entire pipeline and all my data, I want you to pick that one month where data went wrong or that one month where data was missing and just run the partition on that range.

00:34:17.530 --> 00:34:21.800
And so you limit compute, you save resources and get a little bit more efficient.

00:34:22.450 --> 00:34:27.560
And it's just easier to like think about your pipelines because you've got this natural built in partitioning system.

